      "id": "assistant-1774458184123-43s3c3",
      "role": "assistant",
      "text": "I drafted the full keyframe plan for all 5 shots, using **start/end frames for each shot**. That gives you 10 anchors total, which feels right here because the comedy depends on small but important performance shifts rather than big visual resets.\n\n### Keyframe structure\n\n- **SHOT-01-START** — therapy room established  \n- **SHOT-01-END** — confession lands in the room  \n\n- **SHOT-02-START** — psychologist holds the mug in the pause  \n- **SHOT-02-END** — mug set down with measured calm  \n\n- **SHOT-03-START** — psychologist settles into the question  \n- **SHOT-03-END** — question lands cleanly in close-up  \n\n- **SHOT-04-START** — panda gathers emotion before answering  \n- **SHOT-04-END** — “Neither” at the emotional peak  \n\n- **SHOT-05-START** — psychologist looking down at notes before the turn  \n- **SHOT-05-END** — tighter final frame after the slow push-in, glasses adjusted, line lands warm  \n\nA few taste notes:\n- I kept the **acting progression subtle**, especially in shots 2, 3, and 5, because over-expressive keyframes would flatten the deadpan tone.\n- The clearest motion contrast is in **shot 4**, which is where the panda is allowed to spike emotionally.\n- **Shot 5** is planned to support a true visual move, not just a dialogue beat: medium close-up into tighter close-up.\n\nNext I’d turn this into the actual keyframe prompts so the still generations stay consistent with the approved storyboard and character sheets."
    },
